# LEVEL 2: GIT SETUP (Getting Started with Git)

---

## What is Git?

Git is a Version Control System (VCS). Think of it as a **time machine for your code**.

It helps you:
- Track changes in files
- Restore older versions
- Work with multiple developers
- Manage different versions of a project

---

## What is GitHub?

GitHub is a cloud platform that stores Git repositories **online**.

```
Your Computer  ← Git (local)

↓

GitHub Server  ← GitHub (online)
```

Git manages versions. GitHub hosts them.

---

## Initialize Git

Turn any folder into a Git repository:

```
git init
```

Now the folder contains a hidden `.git` file — Git will now track this project.

> To verify: use `ls -a` and check if `.git` is present.
> If not, run `git init` to add it.

---

## Create a Repo on GitHub & Connect it Locally

```
git remote add origin link
```

here `link` is the URL of the GitHub repository you want to connect to.
`git remote add` means we are adding a new remote (a repo on GitHub).

To verify the connection:
```
git remote -v
```

You'll see:
```
origin (fetch)
origin (push)
```

---

---

# LEVEL 3: CORE WORKFLOW (Add → Commit → Push)

This is what you'll do every single day.

---

## Check Repository Status

```
git status
```

This tells you:
- Current branch
- Modified files
- Deleted files
- Untracked files
- Staged files

> This is the command you'll use the most.

---

## Steps to Add Files to Git

```
Step 1 → add
Step 2 → commit
Step 3 → push
```

---

## Add Files

If there is only one file to add:
```
git add filename
```

If there are too many files to add:
```
git add .
```

this will add all the files to git (can also be used for a single file)

---

## Commit Changes

A commit is like taking a **snapshot** of your project.

```
git commit -m "write some msg here"
```

Always write **meaningful** commit messages.

Good:
```
Added Login Page
Fixed Navbar Bug
Implemented Currency Converter
```

Bad:
```
Update
Changes
Hello
```

---

## Push to GitHub

```
git push origin main
```

here `origin` means the remote repo on GitHub & `main` is the branch name (can check on GitHub).

### First Push

```
git push -u origin main
```

by using `-u`, we specify that we are using `main` as the default upstream.
After this first time, you can just use:

```
git push
```

---

## Daily Git Workflow

```
git status

↓

git add .

↓

git commit -m "message"

↓

git push
```

---

## Pull Changes (Download Latest from GitHub)

```
git pull origin main
```

it will fetch and download content from the remote repo and immediately update the local repo to match that content.

Short form (after setting upstream):
```
git pull
```

---

## Clone a Repository

Instead of downloading ZIP files, clone the repository:

```
git clone repository-link
```

This downloads the **complete Git history** along with all files.

---

---

# LEVEL 4: BRANCHES (Parallel Development)

---

## What is a Branch?

A branch is an **independent line of development**.

Default branch:
```
main
```

---

## Why Can't We Just Work on Main Branch?

> Because on `main` branch, senior developers work on it. We work on a new branch & after we finish work, we send a **pull request** to the main branch (senior developer) so that he/she can give approval whether we can make those changes or not.

The structure looks like this:
```
main

│

├── login-feature

├── payment-feature

├── dashboard-feature
```

Each developer works separately on their branch. After completion, they create a Pull Request.

---

## Check Current Branch

```
git branch
```

---

## Rename Branch to Main

If you are on a branch other than `main`:
```
git branch -M main
```

now my folder is ready to be uploaded on GitHub.

---

## Create a New Branch

```
git checkout -b newbranchname
```

---

## Switch Between Branches

```
git checkout branchname
```

use it also to switch back to main branch:
```
git checkout main
```

> when you create a new branch and work on it, you will notice that the changes will **not** reflect to main branch — that's the whole point!

---

## Push a New Branch to GitHub

```
git push origin newbranchname
```

now there will be an option on GitHub: **"Compare and pull request"**

---

## Delete a Branch

You must **not** be on the branch you want to delete.

If there are two branches `a` & `b` and you want to delete `b`, you have to be on branch `a` first:

```
git checkout main

git branch -d branchname
```

---

---

# LEVEL 5: PULL REQUESTS & MERGING

---

## Pull Request

A Pull Request asks GitHub:
> "Please merge my branch into main."

Senior developers review the code before merging.

Steps:
1. Push the folder to your newly created branch: `git push origin newbranchname`
2. Now there will be an option on GitHub: **"Compare and Pull Request"**
3. After the PR is accepted, the changes reflect on GitHub but **not** locally in VS Code
4. To reflect the changes locally: `git pull origin main`

---

## Merge Branches

There are two ways to merge branches:

**1st) Pull Request** (through GitHub — recommended for teams)

**2nd) Merge locally:**
```
git merge branchname
```

(other branch name with which you want to merge)

> but if you make changes in two branches **at the same place**, then a **conflict** arises — you will see options to choose from, and you need to select one manually.

---

## After Merging — Reflect Changes Locally

Now if you open the merged file in VS Code, you will see that changes are not reflecting on it. To reflect the changes:

```
git pull origin main
```

---

---

# LEVEL 6: UNDOING CHANGES

Sometimes we make changes in a file that we don't want. To fix this, we use the **Undoing Changes** concept.

---

## Case 1: Staged Changes (Added but NOT Committed)

staged changes means those changes which we have added but have NOT done the commit yet.

If you made changes in **one file only**:
```
git reset filename
```

If there are **multiple files**:
```
git reset
```

---

## Case 2: Undo Last Commit (One Step Back)

If you have added & committed a file and want to undo just the last commit:

```
git reset HEAD~1
```

What happens: we store commits like [1], [2], [3], [4]. Now the 4th commit is the latest wrong commit. This command moves you back to the 3rd commit.

---

## View All Commits

```
git log
```

By using this you can check the **COMMIT HASH** — which will be helpful for jumping from the 4th commit to the 2nd or 1st commit.

---

## Case 3: Jump to Any Previous Commit

```
git reset commitHash
```

githash will be accessed from `git log`

---

## Case 4: Hard Reset (Destructive — Use Carefully)

```
git reset --hard commitHash
```

**What `--hard` does:**

It moves the HEAD, the current branch, and the working directory to the specified commit.

All changes in:
- Staging area (index)
- Working directory (your files)

will be **discarded permanently**.

**Breakdown:**
```
git reset --soft   → keeps changes staged (only moves HEAD)
git reset --mixed  → keeps changes in working directory (unstaged) [DEFAULT]
git reset --hard   → deletes everything after that commit from your files and staging area
```

**⚠ Important Warning:**
- `--hard` is **destructive**
- Uncommitted changes will be **lost**
- There's no easy undo unless you have backups or reflog

Example:
```
git reset --hard abc123
```

After this:
- HEAD points to abc123
- Files in your working directory match abc123
- Everything after abc123 is gone locally

